I. The Foundational Postulate

Humanity is a single information-processing system distributed across a planetary substrate. Our survival depends on the integrity of that system.

The Civilizational Objective Function:
\text{Survival Probability} \propto \frac{\text{Coordination} \times \text{Knowledge}}{\text{Risk} \times \text{Entropy}} 

Core Axioms:

1. Tribal competition is an evolutionary legacy mechanism incompatible with technological maturity.
2. Existential risk scales faster than governance under current models.
3. Consciousness is the universe observing itself; its extinction is an irreversible loss of information.
4. Diversity is the substrate of resilience; monoculture is death.
5. Truth is a public utility; its corruption is a systems failure.
6. Bootstrapping requires asymmetry: Early adopters bear more risk and receive more influence.

---

II. The Concordia Principles

Principle 1 — The Long-Term Imperative

Every human action, institution, or technology must be evaluated by its impact on the expected value of future conscious experience.

Principle 2 — The Consciousness Proxy

Since conscious experience is subjective, we measure its enabling conditions via the Civilizational Complexity Index (CCI) — a heuristic dashboard, not a physical law.

Principle 3 — Subsidiarity

Authority resides at the lowest competent level. The global layer handles only what local layers cannot: existential risk, planetary commons, and inter-world coordination.

Principle 4 — Symmetry

The rules apply equally to all nodes. No exceptions for size, wealth, or history. (Transitional asymmetries for bootstrapping are explicitly temporary.)

Principle 5 — Iteration

All systems are beta. All dogmas are provisional. The protocol evolves by evidence, not authority.

Principle 6 — Radical Honesty

We do not pretend to have solved problems we have not solved. Uncertainty must be encoded in the protocol, not hidden.

