VI. The Kernel Governance Model

The entity that controls the infrastructure controls the system. Therefore, the Kernel must be governed by a mechanism that prevents capture by any coalition.

The Proof-of-Stake Kernel Council

Composition:

· 51 Node Seats: Distributed proportionally to Stake, where Stake = (Energy Contribution + Data Contribution + Insurance Premiums) over rolling 10-year window.
· Maximum Seat Cap: No single node may hold >10% of voting power.
· Minimum Diversity Requirement: Seats must span at least 5 geopolitical regions and 3 governance types.

Diversity Stake Multiplier — New in 1.3
For the first 50 nodes only, nodes from underrepresented regions or governance types receive a 1.5× multiplier on their effective Stake for seat allocation. The multiplier phases out automatically once 50 nodes are ratified.

Decision Rights:

· Kernel software updates (Refusal Logic, ledger protocols)
· Sentinel Network expansion
· Genesis Fund allocation
· Emergency response activation

Constitution Lock:

· Sections I (Axioms) and V (Handshake Relinquishments) are immutable without 90% supermajority.
· All other sections may be amended by two-thirds vote with one year's notice.

Capture Prevention:

· Rotating Lead Validators: Implementation authority rotates monthly among top 10 nodes by Stake.
· Transparent Execution: All Kernel actions are logged to a public, immutable ledger.
· Judicial Review: Any node may challenge a Kernel decision before the Concordia Tribunal — a randomly selected panel of 21 nodes, excluding the challenger and any directly affected parties.

